    "The strongest case against this proposal is not that Stallion is a poor fund or that the household is unsuited to PMS in principle; it is that the structural foundation required to justify a first PMS allocation has not been established, and the proposal as framed asks the committee to approve a Rs 1 Cr commitment to a less-liquid, higher-cost wrapper while the underlying mandate architecture is itself flagged for clarification. G1 has surfaced three simultaneous band gaps — equity 7.8pp below floor, debt 9.4pp above ceiling, cash 2pp below floor — and the proposed action is only directionally corrective on one of the three; debt remains 9.4pp above ceiling post-action and cash remains at zero. A household whose stated Aggressive mandate has been allowed to drift to 52.2% equity over an extended period is signalling, through revealed behaviour, that the mandate-band conversation itself is unresolved. Deploying the household's first PMS into that unresolved architecture conflates two distinct questions and commits to the more expensive, less reversible answer first.",
